Machine Learning

Machine Learning

  • We’ll give an overview of some basic machine learning tools.

  • The goal here is to give you some options to consider when you are completing your final projects.

  • You are not required to use any particular tool. If a ML model makes sense for your analysis, then its a good way to do something cool, but you can do a good project that relies on simpler approaches.

Machine Learning

We’ll primarily use scikit-learn for machine learning, but this integrates well with libraries like Pandas.

Machine Learning

  • “Machine learning” is kind of a buzzword. But it refers to a broad set of methods for extracting meaning and structure from data to make predictions or analyze relationships.

  • We can class models into two big categories: supervised and unsupervised models.

Supervised learning

In supervised machine learning, we are focused on finding the relationship between a label y and features x.

\[ y = f(x) \]

“Learning” is finding a function f that minimizes future error in recovering y using the predictors x

Supervised learning

What I need for a supervised model

  • An outcome. Keep in mind that you may need to use different models depending on the nature of the outcome you’re predicting. Is it a category? Is it a number?

  • A set of predictors. Importantly, your predictors need to be something you can represent with a number.

  • “training” data used to fit the model, and “testing” data used to assess your ability to predict stuff. Usually you need at least a few hundred observations to train a model.

Basic steps

  1. Identify a set of predictors you think might influence the outcome of interest. Convert your predictors and your outcome to numeric values.
  2. Split the data into “training” and “testing” sets. You’ll use the training data to fit a model, and then evaluate performance on the testing data.
    1. If needed pre-process the training and testing data. Be sure you do this separately for training and testing data to prevent leakage
  3. Fit the model on the training data, and then use it to predict the test data.
  4. Evaluate the results.

Predicting county-level election results

  • For instance, I have data on county-level election results from the 2024 and 2020 elections.

  • My “outcome” here is the percent of the vote in that county that went to Democrats.

  • My predictors (“features”, in ML lingo) include demographic data from the U.S. census.

(In practice, good election prediction models would include a lot more data - including information about things like the national economy, approval ratings, and data from multiple cycles)

Regression

  • Since my outcome is a number, I can use a linear regression to predict election results in each county based on county demographics

  • Linear regression draws a “line of best fit” through the data. It makes some strong assumptions about how our predictors work, but we can also examine relationships between variables.

Regression

Using linear regression: setup

Since we have data from two separate years here, a natural approach would be to use 2020 to fit a model and 2024 results to assess the predictions.

import pandas as pd

election_data = pd.read_csv("election_data.csv")

# select predictors/outcome
predictors = ['num_households','mean_income', 'percent_bachelors']
outcome = 'per_dem'

# Split data
train_X = election_data.loc[election_data['year']==2020, predictors]
test_X = election_data.loc[election_data['year']==2024, predictors]
train_y = election_data.loc[election_data['year']==2020, outcome]
test_y = election_data.loc[election_data['year']==2024, outcome]

Using linear regression: pre-process

Since some of the predictors have very different scales, scaling the data can improve the model performance. But remember to do this separately for training and testing data.

from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler

# Scaling predictors
scaler = StandardScaler()
X_train_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(train_X)
X_test_scaled = scaler.transform(test_X)

Using linear regression: fitting the model

Now we can fit a linear regression model to the data.

from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression

# Fit model on training data
model = LinearRegression().fit(X_train_scaled, train_y)

# Inspecting the coefficients
[(i, j) for i, j in zip(predictors, model.coef_)]
[('num_households', 0.03234986568932909),
 ('mean_income', -0.03806643753299222),
 ('percent_bachelors', 0.10662862843618885)]

Using linear regression: assessing predictions

Its easy to fit a model to data, but can we fit a model on 2020 data that does a good job predicting 2024 results?

To do this, I’ll use the fitted model parameters from 2020, but I’ll use new demographic data from 2024.

Assessing predictions

  • We’ll use various metrics to assess predictions. “Mean squared error” is the average squared difference between the predicted outcome compared the real one. Lower numbers are better.

  • R2 represents the proportion of variation “explained” by the predictive model. Higher numbers are generally better.

from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error
from sklearn.metrics import r2_score

y_pred = model.predict(X_test_scaled)

print("MSE:", mean_squared_error(test_y, y_pred),
      "R2:", r2_score(test_y, y_pred)
      )
MSE: 0.015942709294787957 R2: 0.3407111812314363

Assessing predictions

Plotting predictions against the actual results also helps.

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(4, 4))
ax.scatter(test_y, y_pred, alpha=.5)
ax.axline((0, 0), slope=1, ls="--", c=".0")
plt.xlabel('Actual Results')
plt.ylabel('Predicted Results')
plt.title("Predicted vs. Observed results for 2024 election")
plt.show()

Supervised Learning for Categories

  • What if my “labels” are something like a “yes” or “no” outcome? Regression models “draw a line” through data, but we can’t really “draw a line” through a categorical outcome.

Supervised Learning for Categories

I’m interested in predicting terrorist attacks in 2020 using this data set. But the any_attacks variable is coded as “Yes” or “No”.

gtd = pd.read_csv("gtd_data.csv")

Supervised Learning for Categories

I can “dummify” categorical variables to make them into a 1 or 0 variable. This creates k-1 dummies for each level of the categorical variable, with each taking on a zero or one value:

gtd_dummified = pd.get_dummies(gtd, columns=['any_attacks','any_attacks_prior_year', 'autonomy'],  
                            drop_first=True, dtype='int')

gtd_dummified.head()[['country','any_attacks_yes']]
country any_attacks_yes
0 Afghanistan 1
1 Albania 1
2 Algeria 1
3 Angola 0
4 Argentina 1

Supervised Learning for Categories

But it still doesn’t really make sense to think of drawing a straight line through this.

gtd_dummified.plot.scatter(y = 'any_attacks_yes', x = 'gdp_pcap');

Supervised Learning for Categories

Fortunately, we have lots of models that can work with categorical data.

  • Logistic regression (the closest to a regular regression model) uses a sigmoid function to model the probability the outcome being “TRUE” or 1.

  • Others include: Naive Bayes, Support Vector Machines, Tree classifiers, and neural networks.

Logistic Regression: Setup

We’ll train a logistic regression model. We don’t have data from two different years here, so we’re going to create a “train” and “test” set by randomly leaving out 30% of the observations.

from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
gtd_features = gtd_dummified[['gdp_pcap', 'oil', 'liberal_democracy','political_stability']]
gtd_outcome = gtd_dummified['any_attacks_yes']

train_X, test_X, train_y, test_y = train_test_split(gtd_features,
                                                    gtd_outcome,
                                                    test_size=0.30,
                                                    random_state=20)

We’ll also standardize the predictors in both groups. This isn’t always necessary but some models will fail to converge when the data contains large outliers, so scaling can address this.

scaler = StandardScaler()
X_train_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(train_X)
X_test_scaled = scaler.transform(test_X)

Logistic Regression

We’ll fit a logistic regression model using the training data. And then predict using the test data that was randomly held out. How many of the predictions from the model are correct?

from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression

logitmodel = LogisticRegression(random_state=0).fit(X_train_scaled, train_y)


# predict using the testing data:
predictions = logitmodel.predict(X_test_scaled)



pd.crosstab(predictions, test_y, rownames=['Prediction'], colnames=['Actual Outcome'])
Actual Outcome 0 1
Prediction
0 16 3
1 11 21

Assessing predictions

  • When classifying data into groups, “accuracy” may not be the best metric. If a category is very rare, we can “predict” it easily by just always guessing 0

  • Instead, we’ll use confusion matrices to get a sense of the accuracy of our prediction method.

  • Keep in mind: whether you care more about false positives vs. false negatives is partly a question of interpretation. Which is more important in your setting?

Assessing predictions

from sklearn.metrics import confusion_matrix
from sklearn.metrics import ConfusionMatrixDisplay


cm = confusion_matrix(test_y, predictions)
mat = ConfusionMatrixDisplay(confusion_matrix = cm, display_labels= ['No attacks', "Attacks"] ).plot()
plt.show()

Assessing predictions

  • Precision: the % of predicted positive cases that were actually positive

  • Recall: the % of actually positive cases that were predicted positive

  • Accuracy: the % of predicted cases that are accurate

  • Cohen’s Kappa: a measure of how much predictions are improved compared to a random guess

  • Balanced Accuracy: a measure of accuracy that’s adjusted for imbalanced data

  • F-1: a kind of balanced average of precision and recall (harmonic mean)

I’m personally partial to Cohen’s Kappa and balanced accuracy, because they’re easy to compare across models.

Assessing predictions

Here are some of those stats for this model:

from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score, cohen_kappa_score, f1_score, classification_report, balanced_accuracy_score

print(classification_report(test_y, predictions, 
                            # add target_names to show labels in the report:
                            target_names=['No attacks', 'Attacks']))

print("cohens kappa: ", cohen_kappa_score(test_y,  predictions))
print("balanced accuracy: ", balanced_accuracy_score(test_y, predictions))

Supervised learning: general problems

  • “Overfitting” is a common problem in supervised learning that shows up when we make a model that predicts training data well, but under-performs on the held-out data.

  • The curse of dimensionality: there are a huge number of possible models, and we can’t include everything. Figuring out what to include and what to toss out is a big part of making effective predictive models.

  • In regression, we can try to avoid this by using “ridge” models that automatically trim variables that are less important. See: ridge_regression
